Climate change is predicted to have a variety of impacts on human health, many of which have been extensively reviewed (
 Confalonieri et al. 2007; 
 Ebi et al. 2006, 
 2008; 
 Frumkin et al. 2008; 
 Patz and Olson 2006). Some of these effects are easily intuited: increasing temperatures will likely increase the incidence of heat-related mortality (and decrease the risk mortality from cold exposure); increased drought will result in increased food and water shortages, whereas more frequent and more severe heavy precipitation events will increase the incidence of flood-related injuries and deaths, water-and food-borne illness, and other infectious, respiratory, and skin diseases.
